File: Lesotho's Prime Minister Thomas Thabane must leave office by 22 May. MASERU - Lesotho Prime Minister Thomas Thabane's coalition collapsed in parliament on Monday, leaving him without enough seats to continue governing, the speaker said. National Assembly Speaker Sephiri Motanyane added that Thabane must leave office by 22 May. READ: Lesotho PM confirms plans to step down "We have verified that the four-party coalition agreement has been terminated and there is a formation of a new government," Motanyane announced in parliament. Sam Rapapa, the deputy chairman of Thabane's All Basotho Convention (ABC) party, said all parties had provisionally agreed on Finance Minister Moeketsi Majoro to replace Thabane. READ: Lesotho amends constitution, pressure on Thabane to resign "Thabane is now a caretaker Prime Minister until 22 May when a new Prime Minister is sworn in," Rapapa said.